00:10:09.110 --> 00:10:14.649
and we're actively working this area. So please
stay tuned for more news coming up in the

00:10:14.649 --> 00:10:20.230
near future.
Now, in addition to more users and setting

00:10:20.230 --> 00:10:26.209
out more forms of payment, we really need
to make sure that it's easier for users to

00:10:26.209 --> 00:10:32.110
consume your services and also provide you
as a business more flexibility to charge for

00:10:32.110 --> 00:10:35.920
your services.
So not so long ago, deciding on a business

00:10:35.920 --> 00:10:43.379
model in the app space was actually relatively
straightforward. You would build in an application,

00:10:43.379 --> 00:10:47.720
and then when you're done, you kind of decide,
hey, do I want to launch it as a free application?

00:10:47.720 --> 00:10:53.610
And maybe I have some advertising in it? Or
should I have it as a paid application? And

00:10:53.610 --> 00:10:57.829
that's the choices you have when you go to
the publisher, you know, console, is to pick

00:10:57.829 --> 00:11:00.790
free or paid.
It's a very simple model, but at the same

00:11:00.790 --> 00:11:06.940
time, it also has limitations, because it
didn't have some of the capabilities needed

00:11:06.940 --> 00:11:13.509
for today's business environment.
We now have many more options in Google Play

00:11:13.509 --> 00:11:19.189
to cater to those needs. But that also means,
very importantly, with those options, those

00:11:19.189 --> 00:11:24.009
added options, you really need to start thinking
about your monetization strategy not after

00:11:24.009 --> 00:11:28.850
development, but when you design the application
and as you're developing your application.

00:11:28.850 --> 00:11:32.110
You really kind of have to think of it as
a business of what the application is going

00:11:32.110 --> 00:11:37.019
to do, what the game is going to do, and build
in the monetization method within it.

00:11:37.019 --> 00:11:40.829
So without further ado, let's take a look
at what those options are, and we'll dive

00:11:40.829 --> 00:11:45.699
into a few examples.
So let's start with free.

00:11:45.699 --> 00:11:50.779
Free provides, as we all know, people -- users
like free. It gives you the lowest barrier

00:11:50.779 --> 00:11:54.589
to entry to at least -- for users to at least
try out your application.

00:11:54.589 --> 00:12:04.070
In terms of monetization, free typically means
ad-driven. Your app downloaded as free, but

00:12:04.070 --> 00:12:09.220
you could be earning indirect revenue through
advertising throughout the lifetime of the

00:12:09.220 --> 00:12:12.939
application.
There could be many reasons why you decide

00:12:12.939 --> 00:12:17.480
to go this way, to be ad-driven. It could
be because paid apps are not supported. Or

00:12:17.480 --> 00:12:23.399
it could be in certain countries or if your
content is simply more suitable for free,

00:12:23.399 --> 00:12:28.189
that's what you will decide to do.
Chrix is going to go into this area in-depth

00:12:28.189 --> 00:12:36.800
in the latter part of this presentation.
In premium, this is where the user pays per

00:12:36.800 --> 00:12:42.430
title. So in Google Play, this is a one-time
charge. What that means, it's a one-time charge

00:12:42.430 --> 00:12:48.089
that associates your user account with the
title that you purchased. That means that

00:12:48.089 --> 00:12:54.190
if you paid for an application, even though
you may change your device or you may upgrade

00:12:54.190 --> 00:13:00.139
your system software or later, let's say,
if you add a tablet or add a new device and

00:13:00.139 --> 00:13:05.009
you log on with the same account, if you paid
for that premium title, you will have access

00:13:05.009 --> 00:13:10.279
to it, and you only need to pay for it once,
and you also get all subsequent updates to

00:13:10.279 --> 00:13:13.779
the application as well, without having to
pay again.

00:13:13.779 --> 00:13:18.279
Obviously, for updates, you can also launch,
you know, version 2, Version 3 as a separate

00:13:18.279 --> 00:13:24.450
title that you can charge again. But that,
you know, has its ramifications by itself,

00:13:24.450 --> 00:13:29.319
which is you're kind of splitting your install
base. But that's a different topic.

00:13:29.319 --> 00:13:33.379
So that's free and premium.
And then, finally, there's trial, where you

00:13:33.379 --> 00:13:39.389
typically have a light version, sometimes
limited by functionality, or maybe it's time-bound,

00:13:39.389 --> 00:13:46.540
whereby the user can upgrade to a full version
if they like what they see in the free version.

00:13:46.540 --> 00:13:52.060
This model is particularly popular in premium
games. We see a lot of premium games that

00:13:52.060 --> 00:13:58.360
have a light version and a full version. And,
in fact, as an anecdotal kind of example,

00:13:58.360 --> 00:14:03.930
when we feature something in the Google Play
Store, let's say we feature a paid title or

00:14:03.930 --> 00:14:09.511
premium title, we very often see a big jump
not just in that title, but also in the free

00:14:09.511 --> 00:14:14.389
version of that title as well. So users always
look at these things. Paid, sometimes they'll

00:14:14.389 --> 00:14:20.519
go to the free and if they like what they
see, they come back to pay for the paid version.

00:14:20.519 --> 00:14:27.579
Let's talk about freemium. Freemium is a very
popular topic today, and I'm sure a lot of

00:14:27.579 --> 00:14:33.920
you are hearing about it because of the success
that's getting. Freemium is largely possible

00:14:33.920 --> 00:14:41.769
because of in-app billing capabilities. The
user downloads the game or app for free, and

00:14:41.769 --> 00:14:44.959
further down the line in the application,
you have different in-app products that are

00:14:44.959 --> 00:14:50.920
offered to users, such as virtual currency,
special items, or digital content that you

00:14:50.920 --> 00:14:55.879
purchase within the app itself. This is a
great model, because it allows your users

00:14:55.879 --> 00:15:00.639
to download it without having to pay for it,
invest some time in learning how the game

00:15:00.639 --> 00:15:07.220
works or what the app does, and then have
further offerings for them to purchase. Obviously,

00:15:07.220 --> 00:15:13.139
some apps are better suited for freemium.
We've seen a lot of successes in social casual

00:15:13.139 --> 00:15:20.910
games. Some other applications may not suit
this form of payment very well. Or this type

00:15:20.910 --> 00:15:26.389
of payment very well, which is, for example,
like productivity or business. For example,

00:15:26.389 --> 00:15:30.660
imagine if you have a spreadsheet, and if
you charge 50 cents every time somebody wants

00:15:30.660 --> 00:15:35.490
to print something or format a paragraph,
that's not so cool.

00:15:35.490 --> 00:15:41.160
So some category of applications work; some
don't in the freemium case.

00:15:41.160 --> 00:15:47.189
So let's take a look at how in-app billing
works. I was giving you kind of a quick run-through

00:15:47.189 --> 00:15:53.430
of an example. This is based on the sample
code which is available on developer.android.com.

00:15:53.430 --> 00:15:58.600
We'll do a quick run-through.
So, first, Google Play client application

00:15:58.600 --> 00:16:05.620
which is on the device plays a very central
role in letting your application work with

00:16:05.620 --> 00:16:09.350
the Google Play server.
So your application actually never really

00:16:09.350 --> 00:16:12.569
has to talk to the server except through this
Google Play client.

00:16:12.569 --> 00:16:20.149
We have something which is called market billing
service within the client. And this is when

00:16:20.149 --> 00:16:25.050
you actually set up in purchases, you set
up your product catalogue through the publisher

00:16:25.050 --> 00:16:29.290
console. And you can set different currencies
and so forth by publishing them through the

00:16:29.290 --> 00:16:36.029
Google Play publisher console. And your application
would reference, right, as you -- as you build

00:16:36.029 --> 00:16:40.259
your application, your application will be
making -- exposing those products available

00:16:40.259 --> 00:16:44.120
for purchase within the application. And you
can build your application logic around it.

00:16:44.120 --> 00:16:49.179
Now, typically, this is how an application
would be set up. And, again, this is structured

00:16:49.179 --> 00:16:55.040
after the sample code that we have on developer.android.com.
But, typically, you would have a building

00:16:55.040 --> 00:16:59.739
service set up. The billing service makes
requests, sends billing requests to the market

00:16:59.739 --> 00:17:04.160
billing service. You have a billing receiver,
which receives asynchronous messages back

00:17:04.160 --> 00:17:11.250
from the server. You also have maybe a couple
classes to response -- to respond to the messages

00:17:11.250 --> 00:17:15.050
that you receive through the response handler.
And then you may have a purchase op server

00:17:15.050 --> 00:17:23.730
so that when you confirm that something has
been transacted, you reflect it in the UI.

00:17:23.730 --> 00:17:29.000
And you may also have a security module within
the client itself to handle various different

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:33.540
security aspects.
And then optionally, you can also set up your

00:17:33.540 --> 00:17:38.860
own server to store your transaction status.
It's not something that's required, but it's

00:17:38.860 --> 00:17:43.510
something that's probably good to have. In
the cases where you delivered content, for

00:17:43.510 --> 00:17:48.330
example, it's good to have your own server
and also maybe do tracking of transactions

00:17:48.330 --> 00:17:53.150
and also security validations separately from
the application, which is probably from a

00:17:53.150 --> 00:18:00.450
best practice perspective better than storing
that security mechanism in the client.

00:18:00.450 --> 00:18:06.120
And lastly, there are two types of in-app
purchases, one which is managed; another which

00:18:06.120 --> 00:18:09.200
is unmanaged.
So managed is very similar to when you buy

00:18:09.200 --> 00:18:14.540
an application, where the Google Play Store
will actually keep track of those services

00:18:14.540 --> 00:18:19.500
-- of those items that have been purchased.
Unmerchandising is something which the Google

00:18:19.500 --> 00:18:25.370
Play Store will help you with the transaction
